{
  "texts": [
    "Hence, albeit from a very different channel, this model also implies that AI and digital ad-based business models cause greater voter and party polarization.",
    "At a high level, therefore, our analysis of both channels indicates that AI-powered platforms act as a source of polarization among voters, and political parties respond to this by choosing more polarized policy positions (even more so than the voters).",
    "The ways in which the two channels work are quite different, however.",
    "The social media channel works via the platform's ability to manufacture filter bubbles and makes it more likely that left-leaning (right-leaning) users are exposed to more leftleaning (right-leaning) content.",
    "On the other hand, in the digital ads channel, it is the parties that cater their messages for groups of voters that are more susceptible to believe the ads they receive and thus drive polarization."
  ]
}